title: For Sale:  Lucid HD7 Red Dot Sight
location: Wister Oklahoma, Fort Smith, AR, Oklahoma
postcontent:
I bought this scope for my AR and shot a few rounds through it and decided I wanted a scope with more magnification. It is in the original box with all the paper work. I also have the 2X magnifier with it. 

The LUCID HD7 Red Dot Sight Gen II (HD7) is a quality optic that is gaining favor with many law enforcement and recreational shooters alike. Made extremely durable, reliable and packed full of well thought out user friendly features, the HD7 is always on target.

This red dot sight has a cast aluminum frame that is fully rubber armored, waterproof, shockproof tested to .458 SOCOM, and fogproof made for extreme durability. 1/2 MOA windage and elevation adjustments on external turrets have positive adjustments with a solid audible click.

The sight gives the operator the option of four different reticles: 2 MOA Dot, 2 MOA Dot with Outer Circle, Circle with Crosshairs, Crosshairs.

The HD7 is powered by a common AAA battery for the customers' convenience and an estimated 1000 hours of battery life. The battery cap is o-ring sealed against the elements. The sight powers itself down automatically after two hours of operation.

This Red Dot Sight features two modes of operation, Manual mode and Auto-Brightness mode where a light sensor will keep the reticle at the right brightness regardless of the environment you are shooting from.

The HD7 sight is designed to mount on Weaver as well as Picatinny rails, and is secured by two 13mm 6-point slotted nuts. The mounting base height of the HD7 provides for a lower 1/3rd co-witness when used in conjunction with a BUIS. The mount is an integral part of the optic frame assembly and does not allow for the adapting of quick release type mounts manufactured by other optic companies.



*********************SOLD******************************

This P-64 is in very nice condition.  Number match.  Includes holster, 2 magazines and cleaning tool.  The blue finish show some light holster wear.  The bore is nice and clean.  The 9mm makarov ammo is inexpensive.

Has been modified with Wolff springs to reduce recoil, double action pull and mag release force.  Recoil and double action pull are the two main complaints about this gun. title: For Sale:  Eagle open bolt 45 ACP mark I carbine
postcontent: This is an extremely rare, 100% legal open bolt carbine. The Eagle Carbine was developed and manufactured in small numbers from 1964-68. A man by the name of Bill Ordner developed the .45 ACP Eagle Carbine, patterned around the M3 Grease Gun and used genuine Thompson 1928 wood stocks in their construction. Bill owned the Eagle Gun Company, which he operated out of his house in Stratford, Connecticut. The factory where the Eagle Carbine was actually manufactured, was located in northeast Pennsylvania. Bill would travel to the factory to proof fire new stock and pick up shipments of Eagle Carbines for resale to dealers until his factory was controversially burnt down in 1968. The Eagle Mark I, followed later by the Mark II version, were the first of several open bolt carbines to be manufactured and sold in the 1960's. These were followed by the Spitfire, the Apache and the Commando Carbine which appeared in the early 1970's. All were semiauto carbines that fired either .45 ACP or 9mm pistol cartridges using surplus Thompson, M3 or Sten magazines. The Spitfire's and Apache's were later banned by the ATF and reclassified as "machine guns", in effect making the already rare Eagle Carbine one of the only legal versions of this type of firearm. This particular eagle is good condition, in fact the best I have seen out of the few that still exist.
